06778nam a22008895i 9783110780147DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107801477 a10.1515/97831107801472doi  a(DE-B1597)613774  a(OCoLC)1394872833  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a371.33409400aHow Computers Entered the Classroom, 1960-2000 :bHistorical Perspectives /ced. by Carmen Flury, Michael Geiss. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VI, 240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History of Education and Culture / Studien zur Bildungs- und Kulturgeschichte ,x2748-9531 ;v200tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tComputers in Europe's Classrooms: An Introduction -- tPart I: Case Studies -- tInformatique pour tous, France 1985: Pedagogy, Industry and Politics -- tHow Computers Entered the Classroom in Hungary: A Long Journey from the Late 1950s into the 1980s -- tComputers in the Classrooms of an Authoritarian Country: The Case of Soviet Latvia (1980s-1991) -- tTeachers Translating and Circumventing the Computer in Lower and Upper Secondary Swedish Schools in the 1970s and 1980s -- tJoining Forces: The Promotion of Public-Private Partnerships to Bring Computers into West German Schools in the 1980s -- tComputer Education in Switzerland: Politics and Markets in a Highly Decentralized Country -- tPart II: Trans- and Supranational Perspectives -- tEntangled Media Ecologies: The Nexus of Education and Mass Communication from the Perspective of UNESCO (1945-1989) -- tBeyond the Classroom: Economic Policies and the Past Futures of Education and Training in the European Community, 1970-2000 -- tDefuturization Machines: The OECD's Early Efforts to Plan the Computerized Future of Education -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn the history of education, the question of how computers were introduced into European classrooms has so far been largely neglected. This edited volume strives to address this gap. The contributions shed light on the computerization of education from a historical perspective, by attending closely to the different actors involved - such as politicians, computer manufacturers, teachers, and students -, political rationales and ideologies, as well as financial, political, or organizational structures and relations. The case studies highlight differences in political and economic power, as well as in ideological reasoning and the priorities set by different stakeholders in the process of introducing computers into education. However, the contributions also demonstrate that simple cold war narratives fail to capture the complex dynamics and entanglements in the history of computers as an educational technology and a subject taught in schools. The edited volume thus provides a comprehensive historical understanding of the role of education in an emerging digital society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4a20. Jahrhundert. 4aDigitalisierung. 4aEuropa. 4aSchule. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aEurope.  adigitalization.  apublic education.1 aCardon-Quint, Clémence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlury, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlury, Carmen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeiss, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeiss, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/